{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17475242","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17475242"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:30:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:30:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12573"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12573","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12573"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.6,0.21,0.02,0.05,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5072"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54675"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5072","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5072"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question","status":"accepted","createdAt":"2023-03-04T16:22:48+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-03T19:02:30+09:30","updatedAction":"commented","acceptedAt":"2023-03-19T19:54:15+10:30","editorNotifiedAt":null,"feedbackAt":"2025-09-24 16:04:25"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12573"}},"updatedBy":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"13477"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"342"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40202"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"370"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"2067"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8477"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8512"}]},"lastContribution":{"data":null},"lastRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40202"}},"lastActivity":{"data":null},"lastFeedback":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54675","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54675"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA three-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of a barking cough and intermittent stridor at rest. He has had no rigors or febrile episodes. His parent reports that he has been more irritable with a reduced appetite. He has no significant medical history and no recent sick contacts. His vaccinations are up to date. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears anxious, and there is a harsh inspiratory noise with suprasternal and intercostal retractions. His pulse rate is 120/min, respiratory rate 25/min, blood pressure 100/60 mmHg, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral dexamethasone","Nebulised adrenaline","Intravenous antibiotics","High-flow oxygen therapy","Admission for observation"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis scenario is consistent with moderate croup, a common viral respiratory illness in children usually caused by parainfluenza virus. It is typically characterised by a barking cough, stridor, and increased work of breathing. The duration is usually three to seven days, with the most severe symptoms on days three or four. Treatment depends on the severity at presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral dexamethasone\u003C/strong\u003E is the first-line treatment for mild to moderate croup. It is typically given as a single dose of 0.15-0.6 mg/kg. Dexamethasone is preferred over prednisolone due to its longer half-life, allowing for a single dose. Corticosteroids reduce airway inflammation, improving symptoms and reducing the need for further medical care.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENebulised adrenaline\u003C/strong\u003E is reserved for severe croup, which this child does not currently have. It should be administered if there is evidence of deterioration such as drowsiness, persistent stridor at rest, or hypoxia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E are not appropriate for croup as it is a viral illness. Moreover, obtaining intravenous access may further aggravate the already anxious child.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh-flow oxygen therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is not required unless there are concerns for severe upper airway obstruction or if there is diminished oxygen saturation. This child\u0027s oxygen saturation is within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdmission for observation\u003C/strong\u003E may be necessary in severe cases of croup or if the child is experiencing significant respiratory distress. In this case, the child\u0027s symptoms are moderate, and he can likely be managed as an outpatient after receiving oral corticosteroids.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter administering oral dexamethasone, the child should be observed for a period to ensure improvement. If stridor resolves at rest and work of breathing improves, he can be safely discharged home with appropriate follow-up instructions. Parents should be educated about the expected course of the illness and when to seek further medical attention.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Oral corticosteroids are the first-line treatment for mild to moderate croup.","Clinical assessment is sufficient for diagnosing croup; no investigations are typically required.","Croup is usually a self-limiting viral illness, with symptoms peaking around days 3-4."],"references":["Croup. In: The Royal Children\u0027s Hospital Melbourne clinical practice guidelines [online]. The Royal Children\u0027s hospital Melbourne. 2020. Available at: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/Croup_Laryngotracheobronchitis/","Sizar O, Carr B. Croup. In: StatPearls [Online]. Updated 2022 Jul 25. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK431070/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40202"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12573"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40202","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/40202"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-09T10:39:55+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-09T10:41:03+10:30","number":4,"notes":"","plagiarismCheckedAt":"2024-10-09T10:40:19+10:30","plagiarismScore":11.4,"plagiarismReportUrl":"https://emedici-copyleaks.syd1.digitaloceanspaces.com/plagiarism-report-5072-4.pdf?X-Amz-Content-Sha256=UNSIGNED-PAYLOAD\u0026X-Amz-Algorithm=AWS4-HMAC-SHA256\u0026X-Amz-Credential=DO00QAKVE68N83EBLT2J%2F20250928%2Fsyd1%2Fs3%2Faws4_request\u0026X-Amz-Date=20250928T130053Z\u0026X-Amz-SignedHeaders=host\u0026X-Amz-Expires=601200\u0026X-Amz-Signature=7316c714020eeace5ad01272231307051855c1a4e94c072c1c1d3cecacdfe968"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5072"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54675"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"12201"}},"generation":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":